The environment override makes tests cheap and also gives power users a simple
escape hatch when they want a project-local config file.

<<functions>>=
def config_path() -> Path:
    """Return the configuration file used by mentipy."""

    if override := os.environ.get("MENTIPY_CONFIG"):
        return Path(override)

    return typerconf.platformdirs.user_config_path(
        CONFIG_NAMESPACE,
        appauthor=False,
        ensure_exists=False,
    ) / "config.json"
@

The CLI accepts short keys such as [[port]], but the stored JSON keeps them
under the [[mentipy]] namespace so unrelated settings do not collide.

<<functions>>=
def normalize_config_key(key: str) -> str:
    """Return the fully qualified config key for ``key``."""

    if key.startswith(f"{CONFIG_NAMESPACE}."):
        return key
    return f"{CONFIG_NAMESPACE}.{key}"
@

Loading the configuration is intentionally separated from reading individual
settings.  The rest of the package should not know where the file lives or how
[[typerconf]] persists it; those details are fixed here.  We also seed the
object with a fresh empty mapping, because [[typerconf.Config()]] otherwise
reuses a mutable default across calls, which leaks settings from one missing
config file into the next.

<<functions>>=
def load_config(*, writeback: bool = False) -> typerconf.Config:
    """Return the mentipy configuration."""

    config = typerconf.Config({})
    config.read_config(config_path(), writeback=writeback)
    return config
@

Reading a setting first normalises the key and then falls back to the built-in
defaults.  That two-step lookup is what lets callers pass either [[port]] or
[[mentipy.port]] while still preserving explicit defaults for keys whose value
is normally [[None]].  The generic [[typerconf]] command stores scalar
[[--set]] values as strings, so we also coerce the built-in non-string settings
back to the types the rest of the package expects.

<<functions>>=
def _coerce_setting_value(full_key: str, value: Any) -> Any:
    if isinstance(value, str):
        parsed = parse_config_value(value)
    else:
        parsed = value

    if full_key in (PORT_CONFIG, MIN_PREFIX_CONFIG):
        if isinstance(parsed, int):
            return parsed
        return value

    if full_key in (SHOW_URL_CONFIG, ALLOW_IMAGES_CONFIG):
        if isinstance(parsed, bool):
            return parsed
        if isinstance(parsed, int):
            return bool(parsed)

    return value
@

<<functions>>=
def get_setting(key: str, default: Any = None) -> Any:
    """Return the configured value for ``key``, or ``default``."""

    full_key = normalize_config_key(key)
    fallback = DEFAULT_SETTINGS.get(full_key, default)

    try:
        return _coerce_setting_value(full_key, load_config().get(full_key))
    except KeyError:
        return fallback
@

Writing a setting uses the same normalisation path as reading, so the CLI can
remain concise without creating a second spelling of each configuration key on
disk.

<<functions>>=
def set_setting(key: str, value: Any):
    """Store ``value`` under ``key`` in the mentipy configuration."""

    config = load_config(writeback=True)
    config.set(normalize_config_key(key), value)
@

Listing settings reports the effective values rather than only the values
present in the JSON file.  The CLI now relies on [[typerconf]]'s generic tree
printer, but this helper still gives tests and internal callers one stable view
of Mentipy's built-in defaults, including nullable settings that may not yet be
present on disk.

<<functions>>=
def list_settings() -> dict[str, Any]:
    """Return the effective values of the built-in mentipy settings."""

    return {
        full_key.split(".", 1)[1]: get_setting(full_key, default)
        for full_key, default in DEFAULT_SETTINGS.items()
    }
@

When a config value arrives as text, we first try JSON decoding and only fall
back to the original string when decoding fails.  That is enough to recover the
typed built-in settings from [[typerconf]]'s generic [[--set]] interface.

<<functions>>=
def parse_config_value(raw: str) -> Any:
    """Interpret ``raw`` as JSON when possible, else keep it as text."""

    try:
        return json.loads(raw)
    except json.JSONDecodeError:
        return raw
