\section{Persistent store}

The store itself is small, but the class boundary matters: the HTTP server, the
LaTeX integration, and the CLI can all share the same persistence rules.

<<classes>>=
class Store:
    """Persist questions and answers in a JSON file."""

    def __init__(self, path: str | Path | None = None, min_prefix: int | None = None):
        chosen_path = path or get_setting(STORE_CONFIG, DEFAULT_STORE_PATH)
        chosen_prefix = min_prefix
        if chosen_prefix is None:
            chosen_prefix = int(
                get_setting(MIN_PREFIX_CONFIG, DEFAULT_MIN_PREFIX)
            )

        self.path = Path(chosen_path)
        self.min_prefix = int(chosen_prefix)
        self._lock = _store_lock(self.path)

    <<store methods>>
@

Reading the store on every operation is the simplest way to make the server see
newly compiled questions without introducing cache invalidation.  Missing files
are treated as empty stores, and older or hand-written files are normalised by
adding the top-level collections the rest of the class expects.

<<store methods>>=
def _data(self) -> dict[str, Any]:
    if not self.path.exists():
        return _blank_store()

    with self.path.open(encoding="utf-8") as handle:
        data = json.load(handle)

    data.setdefault("questions", {})
    data.setdefault("answers", {})
    _ensure_registration_serials(data)
    return data
@

Writes go through a sibling temporary file and then [[os.replace]].  The
temporary file may be incomplete if the process dies mid-write, but it never
becomes the real store unless the final replace succeeds.  We dump without
[[sort_keys]] because the order of the [[questions]] dict is now load-bearing:
it encodes the sequence in which questions were last registered, which the
\enquote{Next $\rightarrow$} navigation walks.  Sorting on disk would erase that
information.  Python's JSON library preserves dict insertion order on dump and
recovers it on load, so the round-trip carries the sequence faithfully.

<<store methods>>=
def _write(self, data: dict[str, Any]):
    self.path.parent.mkdir(parents=True, exist_ok=True)
    temp_path = self.path.with_name(f"{self.path.name}.tmp")

    with temp_path.open("w", encoding="utf-8") as handle:
        json.dump(data, handle, ensure_ascii=False, indent=2)
        handle.write("\n")

    os.replace(temp_path, self.path)
