\section{Registration and prefix resolution}

Registration needs four properties.  It must keep old printed URLs stable when
a later question shares the same beginning of the hash; it must let a question
evolve its presentation fields without losing answers, so that a lecturer who
edits a word-cloud's render mode and recompiles sees the new visualisation on
the very next results request; it must produce the same prefix every time the
same content is registered, so old QR codes keep resolving; and it must
preserve the document order of the source slides in the on-disk dict, so the
server can build the \enquote{Next $\rightarrow$} chain from PythonTeX's
natural execution order.

The first three properties came together once we treated issued prefixes as
exact reservations, extended only the newer question on collision, and merged
the freshly serialised question over the existing entry.  The fourth property
needs one extra bit of operational metadata too, but not an explicit build
session marker.  We still piggyback on Python's guaranteed dict insertion
order: every [[register]] call pops the entry (if any) before re-inserting it,
so the question lands at the end of [[data["questions"]]] regardless of where
it sat before.  Alongside that order, we persist a monotonically increasing
registration serial.  The current live lecture sequence is then the newest
contiguous registration run at the end of the dict.  A full rebuild rewrites
exactly that suffix in document order, so dropped slides stay behind as orphans
while the server's book-style navigation can ignore them.

The split between identity and presentation still matters here.  The hash ---
the key into [[data["questions"]]] --- only sees identity fields, so a
re-registration with new presentation hits the existing slot rather than
allocating a fresh prefix.  The refresh path therefore rebuilds the question
payload from scratch and only carries forward keys that do not belong to the
question contract at all.  That is what lets a lecturer revert a presentation
field back to its default without a stale stored value surviving by omission,
while store-owned metadata such as remembered QR targets still carries over.

<<store methods>>=
def register(self, question: Question) -> str:
    """Register ``question`` and return its stable URL prefix."""

    with self._lock:
        data = self._data()
        full_hash = question_hash(question)
        serial = int(data[REGISTRATION_COUNTER_KEY]) + 1
        data[REGISTRATION_COUNTER_KEY] = serial

        if full_hash in data["questions"]:
            existing = data["questions"].pop(full_hash)
            existing_question = question_from_dict(existing).to_dict()
            metadata = {
                key: value
                for key, value in existing.items()
                if key not in existing_question
            }
            refreshed = question.to_dict()
            refreshed.update(metadata)
            refreshed[REGISTRATION_SERIAL_KEY] = serial
            data["questions"][full_hash] = refreshed
            self._write(data)
            return existing["url_prefix"]

        prefix = self._allocate_prefix(full_hash, data["questions"])
        entry = question.to_dict()
        entry["url_prefix"] = prefix
        entry[REGISTRATION_SERIAL_KEY] = serial
        data["questions"][full_hash] = entry
        data["answers"].setdefault(full_hash, [])
        self._write(data)
        return prefix
@

Prefix allocation looks for the shortest readable prefix that does not collide
with a full hash and has not already been issued as an exact reservation.  The
second condition is what keeps an old printed URL valid when a newer question
shares its first characters.

<<store methods>>=
def _allocate_prefix(
    self, full_hash: str, questions: dict[str, dict[str, Any]]
) -> str:
    issued = {meta["url_prefix"] for meta in questions.values()}

    for size in range(self.min_prefix, len(full_hash) + 1):
        candidate = full_hash[:size]
        matches = [hash_ for hash_ in questions if hash_.startswith(candidate)]
        if not matches and candidate not in issued:
            return candidate

    raise RuntimeError("could not allocate a unique URL prefix")
@

The first registration test pins idempotence: recompiling or rerendering the
same question should never mint a new classroom URL.

<<test functions>>=
def test_register_is_idempotent(tmp_path):
    store = Store(tmp_path / "mentipy.json", min_prefix=4)
    question = OpenQuestion("One thing to change?")

    first = store.register(question)
    second = store.register(question)

    assert first == second
@

The presentation-refresh test pins the word-cloud iteration loop.  When a
lecturer changes the render mode in their slide source and recompiles,
the same canonical hash is registered again with a different
presentation payload.  The store must keep the existing prefix and answer
log (otherwise iteration would invalidate live answers) but must update
the stored entry so the next results request reflects the new
visualisation.

<<test functions>>=

def test_register_refreshes_wordcloud_presentation(tmp_path):
    store = Store(tmp_path / "mentipy.json", min_prefix=4)
    initial = WordCloudQuestion("Words?", render="svg")
    prefix = store.register(initial)
    full_hash = store.resolve(prefix)
    store.record(full_hash, "linear algebra")

    revised = WordCloudQuestion("Words?", render="table")
    refreshed_prefix = store.register(revised)

    assert refreshed_prefix == prefix
    rebuilt = store.question(full_hash)
    assert isinstance(rebuilt, WordCloudQuestion)
    assert rebuilt.render == "table"
    answers = store.results(full_hash)["answers"]
    assert [answer["value"] for answer in answers] == ["linear algebra"]
