\section{Public question views}

The HTTP server needs cheap read helpers for rendering pages and the CLI needs a
stable listing for index-like views.

Those read helpers should expose the question contract, not the store's local
housekeeping.  In particular, remembered QR artifact paths are operational
metadata for later regeneration and would leak document-local filesystem layout
if they escaped through [[metadata()]] or [[all_questions()]].  The same goes
for the internal registration serial that the navigation helpers use to recover
the newest live suffix.

<<functions>>=
def _public_question_metadata(meta: dict[str, Any]) -> dict[str, Any]:
    visible = dict(meta)
    visible.pop(QR_TARGETS_KEY, None)
    visible.pop(REGISTRATION_SERIAL_KEY, None)
    return visible
@

<<store methods>>=
def metadata(self, full_hash: str) -> dict[str, Any]:
    """Return the stored metadata for ``full_hash``."""

    return _public_question_metadata(self._data()["questions"][full_hash])
@

Rehydrating a question goes through the public metadata view.  That keeps
operational keys out of the canonical question factory and preserves the same
boundary that external callers see.

<<store methods>>=
def question(self, full_hash: str) -> Question:
    """Return the typed question for ``full_hash``."""

    return question_from_dict(self.metadata(full_hash))
@

The question listing follows the dict's natural iteration order, which after
[[register]]'s pop-then-reinsert is the document order of the last full
build.  Index pages and the CLI listing therefore mirror what a lecturer sees
in their slide deck, and the same order seeds the book-style navigation row on
the post-submit and results pages.

<<store methods>>=
def all_questions(self) -> list[dict[str, Any]]:
    """Return all registered questions in registration order."""

    data = self._data()
    rows = []

    for full_hash, meta in data["questions"].items():
        row = _public_question_metadata(meta)
        row["hash"] = full_hash
        rows.append(row)

    return rows
@

The forward sequence-navigation helper walks only the questions marked live in
the current rebuild.  That keeps an orphaned slide reachable by direct URL
while still preventing its old classroom neighbours from leaking back into the
current lecture's \enquote{Next $\rightarrow$} chain.

<<store methods>>=
def next_question(self, full_hash: str) -> str | None:
    """Return the next live question's hash, or ``None``."""

    hashes = _live_hashes(self._data())
    try:
        index = hashes.index(full_hash)
    except ValueError:
        return None
    return hashes[index + 1] if index + 1 < len(hashes) else None
