\section{Registered images}

Pin-image questions need the registered image bytes available at serving
time, but the JSON store is the wrong place for them: [[record]] rewrites
the whole file on every answer, so embedding even a modest photograph
would multiply the cost of every submission by the image size.  The
bytes therefore live in a sidecar directory derived from the store path
--- [[mentipy.json]] gets [[mentipy-images/]] --- so a server that only
knows the store location can still find them, and copying a store to
another machine means copying one file and one directory.

The files are content-addressed: each image is stored under its own
SHA-256 digest, the same digest the question carries as its identity.
That makes registration idempotent for free (recompiling slides rewrites
nothing), deduplicates an image shared by several questions, and makes
concurrent writers harmless --- two processes racing on the same name
are by construction writing identical bytes.  Orphaned files from
deleted questions are left in place; they are small, and content
addressing means a future re-registration of the same image simply
reclaims them.

<<store methods>>=
def image_dir(self) -> Path:
    """Return the sidecar directory for registered image bytes."""

    return self.path.with_name(f"{self.path.stem}-images")
@

[[save_image]] computes the digest itself rather than trusting a caller,
so a file name can never disagree with the content it addresses.  The
write goes through a sibling temporary file and [[os.replace]], the same
crash-safety pattern as the JSON store: a process dying mid-write leaves
a stray [[.tmp]] file, never a truncated image served to respondents.

<<store methods>>=
def save_image(self, data: bytes) -> str:
    """Store image bytes content-addressed and return their digest."""

    digest = hashlib.sha256(data).hexdigest()
    target = self.image_dir() / digest
    if target.exists():
        return digest

    self.image_dir().mkdir(parents=True, exist_ok=True)
    temp_path = target.with_name(f"{digest}.tmp")
    temp_path.write_bytes(data)
    os.replace(temp_path, target)
    return digest
@

The digest argument to [[load_image]] ultimately comes from a stored
question entry, but a hand-edited store file could put anything there,
and the digest becomes part of a filesystem path.  Validating the
64-hex-digit shape before the path join is the path-traversal guard:
a value like [[../../etc/passwd]] never reaches the filesystem layer.
Missing files yield [[None]] rather than an exception because the server
maps both cases to the same 404.

<<store methods>>=
def load_image(self, sha256: str) -> bytes | None:
    """Return registered image bytes for ``sha256``, or ``None``."""

    if not is_sha256_hex(sha256):
        return None
    target = self.image_dir() / sha256
    if not target.exists():
        return None
    return target.read_bytes()
@

The round trip pins the content-addressing contract: the returned digest
names the file, and loading it returns the exact bytes.

