\section{Answer recording}

Answer recording is the only mutating operation after registration, so it is
where the atomic rewrite matters most.  It is also the last write boundary
shared by the HTTP server and any direct library caller.  Later readers assume
the stored value already matches the registered question type, so
[[Store.record()]] validates and normalises answers before it appends them.

The validation rules mirror the question types.  Single-choice and scale
answers are bounded integers, multi-select and ranking answers are non-empty
collections of unique indices, and open-text and word-cloud answers are strings
within the configured limit.  We normalise the index-collection sequences to
plain lists so the JSON shape on disk is stable no matter whether a caller
passed a list or a tuple.  Ranking adds two checks on top of the multi-select
contract --- a [[top_n]] cap and, for a full ordering, complete coverage of the
option set --- because for a ranking the \emph{order} of the list is the answer,
not merely the membership.  Pin answers are lists of coordinate mappings
bounded by the question's pin cap, with every coordinate confined to the
normalised $[0, 1]$ square.

The dispatcher walks the question types in increasing surface area.  We make
each string-typed arm explicit rather than letting one type fall through to
the other, so the dispatcher reads as a list of contracts: a future
string-accepting question type would otherwise inherit one of these
contracts by accident.

<<functions>>=
def _normalize_recorded_answer(question: Question, value: Any) -> Any:
    if isinstance(question, MCQuestion):
        if question.multi:
            <<normalise multi-select answer>>

        <<normalise single-choice answer>>

    if isinstance(question, ScaleQuestion):
        <<normalise scale answer>>

    if isinstance(question, OpenQuestion):
        <<normalise open-text answer>>

    if isinstance(question, WordCloudQuestion):
        <<normalise wordcloud answer>>

    if isinstance(question, RankingQuestion):
        <<normalise ranking answer>>

    if isinstance(question, PIN_QUESTIONS):
        <<normalise pin answer>>

    raise TypeError(f"unsupported question type: {type(question).__name__}")
@

Multi-select answers arrive as a collection of indices, but JSON should store a
plain list in a stable order.  The loop therefore validates the collection and
builds the exact list that will be persisted, rejecting duplicates because they
would otherwise inflate later percentage calculations.

<<normalise multi-select answer>>=
if not isinstance(value, (list, tuple)):
    raise TypeError(
        "multi-select answers must be stored as a list or tuple"
    )
if not value:
    raise ValueError("choose at least one option")

indices = []
seen = set()
for index in value:
    if type(index) is not int:
        raise TypeError(
            "multiple-choice answer indices must be integers"
        )
    if index < 0 or index >= len(question.options):
        raise ValueError(
            "multiple-choice answer outside the allowed range"
        )
    if index in seen:
        raise ValueError(
            "multiple-choice answer repeats the same option"
        )
    seen.add(index)
    indices.append(index)

return indices
@

Single-choice answers use the same option-index contract as multi-select
answers, but exactly one integer is expected.  Checking [[type(value) is int]]
keeps booleans out, since [[bool]] is an [[int]] subclass but is not a useful
option index in a poll result.

<<normalise single-choice answer>>=
if type(value) is not int:
    raise TypeError(
        "single-choice answers must be stored as an integer option index"
    )
if value < 0 or value >= len(question.options):
    raise ValueError("multiple-choice answer outside the allowed range")
return value
@

Scale answers are also integers, but their valid range belongs to the question
rather than to an option list.  Keeping that check in its own phase makes the
similarity to multiple-choice answers visible while preserving the different
source of the bounds.

<<normalise scale answer>>=
if type(value) is not int:
    raise TypeError("scale answers must be stored as integers")
if value < question.low or value > question.high:
    raise ValueError("scale answer outside the allowed range")
return value
@

Open-text answers are already JSON strings after validation.  The length limit
is enforced before writing so later renderers and exports can trust the stored
log without rechecking every entry.

<<normalise open-text answer>>=
if not isinstance(value, str):
    raise TypeError("open-text answers must be stored as strings")
if len(value) > question.max_chars:
    raise ValueError("open-text answer exceeds the question limit")
return value
@

Word-cloud answers share the same wire shape as open-text answers --- a
single string bounded by the question's character limit --- but they
deliberately use their own arm rather than falling through to the
open-text one.  The aggregation that happens later is different, so
making the contract explicit here keeps the symmetry between input and
output validation visible to a reader.

<<normalise wordcloud answer>>=
if not isinstance(value, str):
    raise TypeError("word-cloud answers must be stored as strings")
if len(value) > question.max_chars:
    raise ValueError("word-cloud answer exceeds the question limit")
return value
@

A ranking answer is the ordered list of option indices the respondent
chose, best first.  It reuses the multi-select contract --- unique
in-range integer indices normalised to a plain list --- and adds the two
checks that make a list an \emph{ordering} rather than a set: it may rank
no more options than [[top_n]] allows, and a full ranking ([[top_n]] is
[[None]]) must cover every option exactly once.  Storing the validated
list here means the mean-rank aggregation can trust that every index is a
real option and that position truly encodes rank.

<<normalise ranking answer>>=
if not isinstance(value, (list, tuple)):
    raise TypeError("ranking answers must be stored as a list or tuple")
if not value:
    raise ValueError("rank at least one option")

option_count = len(question.options)
limit = question.top_n if question.top_n is not None else option_count
if len(value) > limit:
    raise ValueError("ranking answer ranks more options than allowed")

indices = []
seen = set()
for index in value:
    if type(index) is not int:
        raise TypeError("ranking answer indices must be integers")
    if index < 0 or index >= option_count:
        raise ValueError("ranking answer outside the allowed range")
    if index in seen:
        raise ValueError("ranking answer repeats the same option")
    seen.add(index)
    indices.append(index)

if question.top_n is None and len(indices) != option_count:
    raise ValueError("a full ranking must order every option")

return indices
@

A pin answer is a list of coordinate mappings, and both pin question
types share the contract, so one arm dispatches on the [[PIN_QUESTIONS]]
tuple.  Coordinates are normalised to the rendered target, so the closed
interval $[0, 1]$ is the entire validity story --- and because neither
[[NaN]] nor infinity satisfies a closed-interval comparison, the range
check quietly excludes the float specials without naming them.  We
re-store coordinates through [[float]] so the JSON shape is stable even
if a caller passed integers ([[0]] and [[1]] are legal corner pins).
The key allowlist rejects unknown fields eagerly: anything else stored
today would become load-bearing surprise data for tomorrow's renderers.

<<normalise pin answer>>=
if not isinstance(value, (list, tuple)):
    raise TypeError("pin answers must be stored as a list or tuple")
if not value:
    raise ValueError("place at least one pin")
if len(value) > question.max_pins:
    raise ValueError("pin answer places more pins than allowed")

pins = []
for pin in value:
    if not isinstance(pin, dict):
        raise TypeError("each pin must be stored as a mapping")
    if not set(pin) <= {"x", "y", "comment"}:
        raise ValueError(
            "pins only carry x, y and an optional comment"
        )
    normalized_pin = {}
    for axis in ("x", "y"):
        if axis not in pin:
            raise ValueError(f"each pin needs an {axis} coordinate")
        coordinate = pin[axis]
        if type(coordinate) not in (int, float):
            raise TypeError("pin coordinates must be numbers")
        if not 0 <= coordinate <= 1:
            raise ValueError("pin coordinates must lie in [0, 1]")
        normalized_pin[axis] = float(coordinate)
    if "comment" in pin:
        <<normalise pin [[comment]]>>
    pins.append(normalized_pin)

return pins
@

Comments are only accepted when the question opted in, because the
results page renders them back to the lecturer --- a question that never
asked for prose should never accumulate it.  Empty strings are dropped
rather than stored: the web form submits a comment input for every pin,
so an untouched field must not show up as a blank row in the results.

<<normalise pin [[comment]]>>=
comment = pin["comment"]
if not isinstance(comment, str):
    raise TypeError("pin comments must be strings")
if comment and not question.allow_comment:
    raise ValueError("this question does not accept pin comments")
if len(comment) > PIN_COMMENT_MAX_CHARS:
    raise ValueError("pin comment exceeds the length limit")
if comment:
    normalized_pin["comment"] = comment
