@

\section{Results aggregation}

The result view aggregates answers according to the question type, but it
also has to support two cross-cutting concerns the lecturer expects from a
classroom poll.
\begin{description}
\item[Time-window filtering] A question reused across lectures, or even
  across years, accumulates every answer it has ever received under the
  same canonical hash.  The lecturer wants to see \emph{just this hour}
  or \emph{just today} as easily as the lifetime view, without that
  pooling becoming an obstacle.
\item[Descriptive statistics] Counts alone do not tell a lecturer whether
  the class agrees, splits, or drifts; means and standard deviations make
  scale results actionable, and a mode callout makes multiple-choice
  results readable at a glance.
\end{description}
Both concerns are read-side filters and computations over the same answer
log---no schema change is needed because every answer already carries a
UTC timestamp.  We keep the (filtered) raw log in the returned structure
because the CLI export and the JSON results endpoint still need it;
aggregated counts and statistics ride on top so HTML, JSON, and CLI
consumers all read the same numbers.

<<constants>>=
RESULTS_WINDOW_DELTAS = {
    "hour": timedelta(hours=1),
    "day": timedelta(days=1),
    "all": None,
}
@

Unknown values fall back to [[\"all\"]] so a stray query string can never
wedge the page; the explicit allow-list also keeps the policy auditable
in one place.

<<store methods>>=
def results(self, full_hash: str,
            *, window: str = "all") -> dict[str, Any]:
    """Return aggregated results for ``full_hash``.

    The optional ``window`` keyword filters the answer log by recency.
    Accepted values are ``"hour"`` (the last 60 minutes), ``"day"``
    (the last 24 hours), and ``"all"`` (default; the entire history).
    Unknown values are treated as ``"all"``.
    """

    <<load metadata and apply window filter>>
    <<assemble base results dict>>

    if isinstance(question, MCQuestion):
        <<add MC counts and stats>>
    elif isinstance(question, ScaleQuestion):
        <<add scale counts and stats>>
    elif isinstance(question, OpenQuestion):
        <<add open-text stats>>
    elif isinstance(question, WordCloudQuestion):
        <<add wordcloud frequencies>>
    elif isinstance(question, RankingQuestion):
        <<add ranking mean ranks>>
    elif isinstance(question, PIN_QUESTIONS):
        <<add pin summary>>

    return results
@

Loading metadata is unchanged from the previous implementation; the new
behaviour is the window filter.  We compute the cutoff once and keep
answers whose ISO timestamp is at or after it.  The writer always emits
the [[Z]] suffix for UTC, but [[datetime.fromisoformat]] only learnt to
parse [[Z]] in Python~3.11.  Rather than raise the supported Python
floor or pull in [[dateutil]], we substitute [[Z]] back to [[+00:00]]
before parsing --- the inverse of the substitution the writer applied
when emitting the timestamp.

<<load metadata and apply window filter>>=
data = self._data()
meta = data["questions"][full_hash]
question = question_from_dict(meta)
all_answers = list(data["answers"].get(full_hash, []))

delta = RESULTS_WINDOW_DELTAS.get(window)
if window == "all" or delta is None:
    answers = all_answers
else:
    cutoff = datetime.now(timezone.utc) - delta
    answers = [
        answer for answer in all_answers
        if datetime.fromisoformat(answer["ts"].replace("Z", "+00:00"))
        >= cutoff
    ]
@

The base structure echoes back which window actually applied so HTML
and JSON consumers can render the right active filter; mismatched values
collapse to [[\"all\"]] before they reach the response.

<<assemble base results dict>>=
applied_window = (
    window if window in RESULTS_WINDOW_DELTAS else "all"
)
results = {
    "hash": full_hash,
    "url_prefix": meta["url_prefix"],
    "question": question.to_dict(),
    "window": applied_window,
    "total": len(answers),
    "answers": answers,
}
@

For multiple-choice questions we count per option and add a percentage
breakdown plus the modal index.  Percentages are computed against the
number of \emph{respondents} so a single-choice poll's bars sum to
100\,\%; for a multi-select poll the bars are independently meaningful
(\enquote{60\,\% of respondents picked A}), even though they may sum
past 100\,\%.

<<add MC counts and stats>>=
counts = [0] * len(question.options)
for answer in answers:
    selections = (
        answer["value"] if question.multi else [answer["value"]]
    )
    for index in selections:
        if 0 <= index < len(counts):
            counts[index] += 1
denominator = len(answers) or 1
results["counts"] = counts
results["percentages"] = [
    count / denominator * 100 for count in counts
]
results["mode_index"] = (
    max(range(len(counts)), key=counts.__getitem__)
    if answers else None
)
@

For scale questions we keep the per-bucket histogram and add descriptive
statistics over the flat list of numeric answers.  We use the population
standard deviation [[statistics.pstdev]] because each poll \emph{is} the
whole population we sampled---there is no larger population we are
estimating from a sample, so the Bessel correction would only confuse a
lecturer reading the number.

<<add scale counts and stats>>=
counts = {
    value: 0 for value in range(question.low, question.high + 1)
}
values = []
for answer in answers:
    value = answer["value"]
    values.append(value)
    if value in counts:
        counts[value] += 1
results["counts"] = counts
if values:
    results["mean"] = statistics.mean(values)
    results["median"] = statistics.median(values)
    results["stddev"] = (
        statistics.pstdev(values) if len(values) > 1 else 0.0
    )
    results["min"] = min(values)
    results["max"] = max(values)
else:
    results["mean"] = None
    results["median"] = None
    results["stddev"] = None
    results["min"] = None
    results["max"] = None
@

For free-text answers, the summary that helps a lecturer most is the
average answer length.  It discriminates between one-word reactions and
substantive paragraphs at a glance, and it is invariant to the actual
content (which the JSON export carries verbatim for downstream analysis).

<<add open-text stats>>=
lengths = [len(answer["value"]) for answer in answers]
results["avg_length"] = (
    statistics.mean(lengths) if lengths else None
)
@

For word-cloud answers, the summary every renderer consumes is the same
descending list of (word, count) pairs.  We delegate the counting to
the question itself --- the question already knows whether to split on
whitespace, what minimum length applies, and which stop-word set is
active --- and surface two scalar stats for the lecturer's overview:
the total number of counted tokens (after filtering) and the number of
distinct words.  Together they describe the cloud at a glance:
[[total_tokens]] tells whether the cloud is busy or sparse,
[[unique_words]] tells whether the answers were diverse or clustered.

<<add wordcloud frequencies>>=
frequencies = question.frequencies(answers)
results["frequencies"] = [
    [word, count] for word, count in frequencies
]
results["unique_words"] = len(frequencies)
results["total_tokens"] = sum(count for _, count in frequencies)
@

A ranking aggregates into a single consensus number per option: its mean
rank across the respondents who ranked it.  Because an answer is an
ordered list of option indices, the rank an answer assigns to an item is
just its position plus one, so we accumulate a sum and a count per option
in one pass.  An option that no respondent ranked --- possible whenever
[[top_n]] is set --- has no mean, so we record [[None]] rather than divide
by zero, and place those options last in [[order]].

We expose two parallel views.  [[mean_ranks]] is aligned to the option
list so a caller can look up any option by index; [[order]] is the option
indices sorted best-first (lowest mean rank), which is what the bar charts
render.  Sorting on a [[(unranked, mean)]] key keeps the comparison total
even when some means are [[None]]: ranked options sort by ascending mean,
and the never-ranked ones fall to the end without comparing [[None]] to a
float.

<<add ranking mean ranks>>=
option_count = len(question.options)
rank_sums = [0] * option_count
rank_counts = [0] * option_count
for answer in answers:
    for position, option_index in enumerate(answer["value"]):
        if 0 <= option_index < option_count:
            rank_sums[option_index] += position + 1
            rank_counts[option_index] += 1
mean_ranks = [
    (rank_sums[index] / rank_counts[index])
    if rank_counts[index] else None
    for index in range(option_count)
]
results["mean_ranks"] = mean_ranks
results["rank_counts"] = rank_counts
results["order"] = sorted(
    range(option_count),
    key=lambda index: (
        mean_ranks[index] is None,
        mean_ranks[index] if mean_ranks[index] is not None else 0.0,
    ),
)
@

A pin summary is deliberately raw: the flat list of every pin in the
window, plus its length.  We considered precomputing a binned heatmap
here, but binning resolution is presentation --- the terminal wants a
handful of character cells while the HTML page wants a fine blurred
grid --- so any grid stored here would couple every renderer to one
choice.  The flat list is small (each answer carries at most
[[max_pins]] mappings), already JSON-clean for the export endpoint, and
each renderer bins it at its native resolution.  [[pin_count]] differs
from [[total]]: the former counts pins, the latter respondents, and a
multi-pin question needs both to describe participation.

<<add pin summary>>=
results["pins"] = [
    pin for answer in answers for pin in answer["value"]
]
results["pin_count"] = len(results["pins"])
@

